ifferent purposes. and that comes into the picture.AI can commotion with the main area of AI.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, 'https://inboxtechs.com/blog/india-is-now-an-ai-hub-the-good-future-in-ai', '1671193916.webp', 'The Good Future In AI', 'index follow', NULL, NULL, 'india-is-now-an-ai-hub-the-good-future-in-ai', NULL, NULL, 'shyam', 'Ankur', '1', NULL, '2022-11-18 06:08:08', '2022-12-30 17:12:41'),
(12, 'AI in Agriculture', 'As the 21st century moves ahead toward technology, many business sectors like healthcare, healthcare, automotive, manufacturing, finance, agriculture, etc are moving towards automation to increase productivity and efficiency.', '<p>Artificial intelligence is also known as the deep learning function that imitates the human brain in processing data and creating patterns for use in decision-making including modern techniques for image processing.</p><p>Different techniques are used to analyze various agriculture problems such as disease detection, fruit or plant classification, and crop management process.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h4><strong>Artificial Intelligence (AI) in Agriculture Market Overview:</strong></h4><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The global artificial intelligence (AI) in agriculture market size stood at $852.2 million in 2019, and it is expected to reach $8,379.5 million by 2030, exhibiting a CAGR of 24.8% during the forecast period (2020–2030). The major factors positively impacting the market include the increasing penetration of the internet of things (IoT) in the agriculture industry, rising demand for high crop yield, growing focus on enhanced crop management, and surging utilization of drones for pesticide spraying. Among all regions, North America retained the largest share of AI in the agriculture market in 2019 as its capability to adopt higher technologies in agriculture.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h4><strong>Use of Artificial Intelligence in Agriculture:</strong></h4><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Weather Forecasting</strong> – We all know how weather conditions have been deteriorating. With climatic changes and increasing pollution, it has become difficult for farmers to analyze the right time to sow the seeds. Therefore AI comes into the picture, farmers can analyze weather conditions by using weather forecasting which helps them understand the type of crop that can be grown and when should seeds be sown.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Monitoring of soil and crop health –&nbsp;</strong>Due to a lot of deforestation and farm fires, the quality of the soil is worsening. Therefore a German-based Start-Up named PEAT has come up with an AI-based application that helps farmers to analyze nutritional deficiencies and understand what diseases the plants can have. The farmer can capture images of plants using smartphones. We can also see soil restoration techniques with tips and other solutions through short videos on this application.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Using Drones to analyze crop health-&nbsp;</strong>Drone-based Ariel imaging solutions for monitoring crop health are in thing these days. They produce precise 3-D maps for early soil analysis, useful in planning seed planting patterns. In this technique, data is captured by the drone and then transferred to USB into a computer which is later analyzed by experts.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>It has a system to detect pests -</strong> Pest management is among the most important activities for a farmer. Monitoring all different species visually might not be possible, especially in large quantities. Therefore AI enables farmers. AI systems use satellite images and compare them with historical data using AI algorithms and detect if any insect has landed and which type of insect has landed like the locust, grasshopper, etc. then later it sends alerts to the farmers on their smartphones so that they can analyze and understand the type of pests and take required precautions.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1673333933.png', 'ai-in-agriculture', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ai-in-agriculture', NULL, NULL, 'Ankur', NULL, '1', NULL, '2023-01-10 12:28:53', '2023-01-10 12:28:53'),
(13, 'Predictive Analytics and the Future of Cyber-security', 'Today cyber-attack may happen every day and we don\'t know if the cyber-attacker may be our well-wisher or our team also. cyber-attack may happen every day.\r\n\r\nPredictive analytics can discover like radar that shows the enemy approaching, these analytics determine when and where attacks may occur. This gives your company time to raise the alarm.', '<h4><strong>Explore the Landscape of Predictive Analytics:</strong></h4><p><a href=\"https://inboxtechs.com/\">Predictive Analytics</a> have the power to proactively help the business identify security threats. Instead of only focusing on the “infection stage” of an attack, enterprises can detect future incidents and maximize prevention. Just as IBM’s mobile analyzer detects weaknesses within your applications, the hacker bots use complex analytics and big data to sniff out vulnerabilities before an attack.</p><h4><strong>Understand Where Predictive Analytics Stand Today:</strong></h4><p>Coupling machine learning with predictive analytics will enable cyber-security to shed its current cumbersome blacklist strategy and detect impending threats with confidence. Signature-free security allows businesses to finally keep up with aggressive and tech-savvy hackers. Cyber threats of the future call for cyber-security of the future – and I’m placing my bets on the pivotal technologies of predictive analytics and artificial intelligence.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/1UQmJRSnKInnDpzcGipFyzZdsv99nL5OakUOqcRP_ShmtEh_7OwT6ibLdiYBrt7g3Lccn6k19EAQPx2XBTLwSVMs-mdxlVqDbqoK_n8MVmJ8He3bNHyBVscI3k4u6pJ-hjoQs8vBDtj9_Qe7vxNIGSY\"></figure><p>As the world becomes increasingly digital, the need for robust cybersecurity measures has become more important than ever before. Organizations must safeguard their sensitive data from cyberattacks that can cause irreparable damage to their reputation, financial stability, and customer trust. In response to this growing threat, many organizations have started to rely on predictive analytics to enhance their cybersecurity capabilities.</p><p>Predictive analytics is the use of data, statistical algorithms, and machine learning techniques to identify the likelihood of future outcomes based on historical data. In cybersecurity, predictive analytics can be used to identify potential threats and vulnerabilities in an organization\'s network infrastructure before they are exploited by cybercriminals.</p><p>The future of cybersecurity lies in predictive analytics, as it allows organizations to take a proactive approach to cybersecurity rather than simply reacting to attacks. With predictive analytics, cybersecurity professionals can anticipate potential threats and vulnerabilities, and take preemptive measures to prevent them from occurring.</p><p>One of the biggest advantages of predictive analytics in cybersecurity is its ability to analyze vast amounts of data from various sources, including network traffic logs, system event logs, user behavior data, and threat intelligence feeds. By analyzing this data, predictive analytics can identify patterns and anomalies that might indicate potential threats or vulnerabilities.</p><p>For example, if a user account logs in from a new location, the system may flag it as suspicious and alert the security team. Alternatively, if a system log shows an unusually high number of failed login attempts, the system may indicate a brute force attack is underway, and the security team can take steps to prevent it.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/rD92I3VB_ER1sL3XxmT_P2ti12NiAuL9cCGeWYtuJA2tovtm33EkEpYSVJN0EENT7JKfdnDOrhj_eNS7fAU7PF-qhmby-rPOwVzBgQVIVWgtpwTjinvnlSXtGn5xYGnxb1LaIihAiLXvtNU3E4E0XVE\" alt=\"Predictive Analytics and the Future of Cyber-security\"></figure><p>Predictive analytics can also help organizations identify and respond to emerging threats quickly. Cybersecurity threats are constantly evolving, and new types of attacks are being developed every day. With predictive analytics, cybersecurity professionals can stay ahead of the curve by monitoring threat intelligence feeds and analyzing data to identify new and emerging threats.</p><p>Moreover, predictive analytics can help organizations optimize their cybersecurity resources by identifying areas that require attention. By analyzing data, predictive analytics can determine which security measures are most effective and which ones require improvement. This can help organizations prioritize their cybersecurity efforts and allocate resources more effectively.</p><p>However, there are also some limitations to predictive analytics in cybersecurity. One of the biggest challenges is the need for high-quality data. Predictive analytics algorithms rely heavily on accurate and reliable data to produce accurate results. If the data is incomplete or inaccurate, the algorithm may produce false positives or false negatives, which can lead to missed threats or wasted resources.</p><p>Another challenge is the complexity of cybersecurity environments. Cybersecurity professionals must manage a vast array of devices, applications, and networks, each with their own unique security risks and vulnerabilities. Predictive analytics can help identify and manage these risks, but it requires a deep understanding of the organization\'s cybersecurity infrastructure and the potential threats that it faces.</p><p>In conclusion, predictive analytics is a powerful tool that can enhance an organization\'s cybersecurity capabilities by identifying potential threats and vulnerabilities before they can be exploited by cybercriminals. However, it is important to recognize the limitations of predictive analytics and the need for high-quality data and expert analysis. As cybersecurity threats continue to evolve, organizations must continue to invest in innovative cybersecurity solutions like <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Predictive_analytics\">predictive analytics</a> to stay ahead of the curve and protect their sensitive data.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1673335585.webp', 'predictive-analytics-and-the-future-of-cyber-security', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'predictive-analytics-and-the-future-of-cyber-security', NULL, NULL, 'Ankur', 'Ankur', '1', NULL, '2023-01-10 12:56:25', '2023-02-23 18:38:12'),
(14, 'IOT In Agriculture: 8 Technology Use For Smart Farming', 'With growing technology, we make our farming technology smart and good also we make our farms smart in our homes. like in the home we control more devices by smartphone or Alex. so we make a thing also work for farms. there are many devices for farms also with good smart devices.', '<p>Smart Agriculture: As we know that we have many devices for smartphones, cameras, etc.. so by using these devices we can convert our traditional farming to smart farming. as we all have many resources for this in the market. like we can control some tools by giving direction to the tool.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/5YocqxkmAlpuZ8j5bZ6zQYZiXPkz4M6EXW7h3NZ24o54GRVzdwdzpYeJ9hi-FqyTZYPZfXcgLICMHIlEccSP1EKnXBzIz_BIr96BuAAZ4lLYfI4wDi046E9xK5GEA5ijrAog4bLRy11v2TKC_ZbHZJM\" alt=\"iot-in-agriculture\"></figure><h4><strong>The Benefits of smart farming:</strong></h4><ol><li>Data Ton by data collected by smart &nbsp;agriculture sensors:</li><li>Better control of internal processes as a result we have lower production risks.</li><li>cost management and reduce waste production give you good productivity as compared to regular farming.</li><li>Increase business efficiency.</li><li>Increase production time and also get a good quality product every time.</li></ol><h4><strong>Application of IoT agriculture :</strong></h4><h4><strong>&nbsp;1. Climate mountaineer:</strong></h4><p>There is a device that where you to mountaineer climate change or u can get an idea of climate is suitable for farming or not.</p><h4><strong>2. Greenhouse automation:</strong></h4><p>Typically, farmers use manual intervention to control the greenhouse environment. The use of IoT sensors enables them to get accurate real-time information on greenhouse conditions such as lighting, temperature, soil condition, and humidity.</p><p><a href=\"https://easternpeak.com/works/iot/\">GreenIQ</a> is also an interesting product that uses smart agriculture sensors. It is a smart sprinkler controller that allows you to manage your irrigation and lighting systems remotely.</p><h4><strong>3. Crop Management:</strong></h4><p>One more type of IoT product in agriculture and another element of precision farming is crop management devices. Just like weather stations, they should be placed in the field to collect data specific to crop farming; from temperature and precipitation to leaf water potential and overall crop health.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/8GKfEtuxuRY281GP97ltIEQc6jwNjhCL7l-egQUQQYWC1eHEFtOtSGmwV-mq8IibuSXJeuXVuntMkSUsdSqhlPYsevuzT1rWEFYHVWJAWaENZ90d98g4-J4-lVsC-wgVa23XsBFW9TmIH2lzpC92B1o\" alt=\"iot-in-agriculture\"></figure><h4><strong>4. Precision farming:</strong></h4><p>By using IoT sensors, farmers can collect a vast array of metrics on every facet of the field microclimate and ecosystem: lighting, temperature, soil condition, humidity, CO2 levels, and pest infections. This data enables farmers to estimate optimal amounts of water, fertilizers, and pesticides that their crops need, reduce expenses, and raise better and healthier crops.</p><p>Crop-X builds IoT soil sensors that measure soil moisture, temperature, and electric conductivity enabling farmers to approach each crop’s unique needs individually. Combined with geospatial data, this technology helps create precise soil maps for each field. Motive offers similar services, helping farmers reduce waste, improve yields, and increase farm sustainability.</p><h4><strong>5. End-to-end farm management systems:</strong></h4><p>A more complex approach to IoT products in agriculture can be represented by the so-called farm productivity management systems. They usually include a number of agriculture IoT devices and sensors, installed on the premises as well as a powerful dashboard with analytical capabilities and in-built accounting/reporting features.</p><h4><strong>6. Drow:</strong></h4><p>By using the drown we can take a look at what happens in farming and also take look for farming and also monitoring the activity which goes on on the farm on our phones.</p><p>So, by this, we can make our farm smart like our home, by using more tools. in agriculture so that we can get a good result in this.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1673345451.png', 'IOT In Agriculture', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'iot-in-agriculture-8-technology-use-for-smart-farming', NULL, NULL, 'Ankur', 'Ankur', '1', NULL, '2023-01-10 15:40:51', '2023-02-23 17:09:20');
