(53, 'What is an Identity Management System?', 'By definition, an Identity Management System also referred to as Identity Management and Access System, is a security framework that can be implemented to provide authorized access to technology resources by authenticating users using a token-based approach.', '<h4><strong>Identity Management System Definition</strong>&nbsp;</h4><p>By definition, an Identity Management System also referred to as Identity Management and Access System, is a security framework that can be implemented to provide authorized access to technology resources by authenticating users using a token-based approach.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/wRo0dJCVjsEwf85pzcWB-rIB3bPRp2WmaZmbva--TK0_y3XpEZGBjYHs1eEG8nUAlZEN-ERwnc7VUJ7tuKHDIci95Pt3a-GdGeOBHTwyAhhBJlvtAzXrdSc2f-k70vU3ZRg_s3TrrGNzPaAnhRP2hDM\" alt=\"identity-management-system\"></figure><p>Following the principle of separation of concern, each component (or sub-system) handles a singular logical function and depends on the other components for operations that are out of the scope of the component. An Identity Management System should consist of logical components for the following services:</p><p><strong>An Authentication Service</strong></p><p>responsible for authenticating users and providing self-service for users to reset passwords and sign up, among other things.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;A Federation Service</strong></p><p>responsible for web application cross-domain Single Sign-On.</p><p><strong>A Token Service</strong></p><p>liable for the issuance of security tokens and introspection. primarily for API access and accessibility to the contemporary web and mobile applications.</p><p><strong>A User Management Service is</strong></p><p>accountable for user provisioning procedures.</p><h4><strong>The Authentication Service</strong></h4><p>As a hub (or multiplexer) for serving various identity sources, such as social identities, strong identities, or any other identity source, an authentication service ought to be constructed. The entity that is able to provide an answer to the question of who the user is based on the identity source it provides is referred to as an identity source or an authenticator. It is possible to add new authenticators to the system without having to update the dependent systems, such as the websites or applications that use these identities.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/x8qsll0fxovjWfgLm8m2jqVsX9CJtT6rWWTLuS5Hmz7Pa8Q8TUvqfMinn1WDCbWUw4Aqh5x8yCH99l-c8D7wYkbjA9rR4uRHhFMaz0NZhjVRar3EAu836IQUVfABBVBQXK5_cyCimX8A4BsFJVSBhjQ\" alt=\"identity-management-system\"></figure><p>Because there are so many different approaches that a system can take to identify a user, authentication is an inherently difficult problem to standardize. One method may authenticate the user by determining the user\'s physical network, while another may send a letter with a pin code through physical mail services.</p><p>As a result, the authentication service is required to act as a broker between applications that require user authentication and these various authentication methods. Applications rarely communicate directly with the authentication service; instead, they use standard protocols to request authentication from either the Federation Service or the Token Service. When required, these, in turn, communicate with the Authentication Service.</p><p>Separating non-standard integration from standard protocol functions like federation and token issuance is a clear advantage of this.</p><h4><strong>The Token Service</strong></h4><p>Tokens are issued and verified by a Token Service, also known as a Security Token Service (STS). The types and profiles of these tokens vary. To send tokens to clients, an STS uses different protocols; Some of them are not standardized, while others are. OAuth and WS-Trust are the most frequently used standard protocols that an STS implements.</p><p>An STS is typically referred to as an OAuth Authorization Server (AS), a specialized type of token service when implementing the OAuth protocol. Two types of tokens are issued by an AS: Refresh Tokens and Access Tokens (ATs) Clients typically receive tokens \"by value\" or \"by reference.\"</p><p>See OAuth Token Types The JSON Web Tokens (JWTs) are the tokens that are passed by value the most frequently. When mobile is not the primary use case, SAML tokens are sometimes passed by value as well. Any non-standard tokens are always passed by reference. By-ref tokens are widely used despite the lack of standardization.</p><p>OAuth, WS-Trust, and other protocols that an STS might use are all \"active protocols,\" which means that for a token to be issued and/or validated, a client must actively participate in the message exchange. The customer cannot simply convey the message. A token can only be issued and/or validated if active clients perform actions. Mobile apps, dynamic Web apps running on a Web server, and desktop applications are typical examples of active clients. Both of these protocols are used to facilitate delegated authorization and broker trust between security realms. Asymmetric cryptography is typically used to sign messages and tokens in trust brokering. A trusted authority signs the asymmetric keys that are used to compute these digital signatures. Consequently, the trust is mediated by the trust that each party has in an impartial third party. Most of the time, this outside authority is a root Certificate Authority (CA) like Thawte or Verisign.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/vhggwZf2GjlYW-DRrZwIoyes08QacttO5ajm7liArNcyuEPp94Izl_0ckt9NrDH-ARmx79rWDjC_jmk1j1LdDjWShj66VCxb7qEYJ3jDwW4_vCamzZgCDqfCyrR_uCQadHEHyIWIacMWM_uKVg8PU9I\" alt=\"identity-management-system\"></figure><p>A four-party trust model is used to accomplish delegated authorization rather than the simpler three-party model. The STS grants a specific client application permission to act on behalf of an end user or Resource Owner (RO) in a four-party system. It asserts that the Resource Server (RS) or API, the fourth party, receives the tokens. This API determines whether the delegated authorization complies with its own security policy after verifying the token\'s authenticity through mutual faith in the STS.</p><h4><strong>The Federation Service</strong></h4><p>A Federation Service is very similar to a Token Service. An application known as a Federation Service facilitates trust between organizations. However, in contrast to the Token Service, a Federation Service provides \"passive clients\" with cross-domain identity propagation. A passive client simply facilitates communication between the Federation Service and the actors that rely on it for identity federation, as opposed to the active client described in the preceding section, which computes the inputs and outputs required to determine security tokens from a Token Service. A Web browser is the classic example of such a client. Web Single Sign-on (SSO) is the outcome of the client\'s passive participation in the message exchange. SSO lets a user move from one security context to another without having to re-authenticate.</p><p>Protocols that are tied to HTTP are used by a Federation Service to support browser clients. As with WS-Federation, a protocol that is frequently implemented by a Federation Service, these protocols may occasionally extend those utilized by an STS with active clients. SAML and old OpenID are two other typical protocols that a Federation Service will be able to support. Other less well-known protocols or proprietary protocols are supported by some Federation Services. OpenASelect is one such protocol, but it is only used in a few specific industries and geographies.</p><h4><strong>OpenID Connect layers identity atop OAuth.</strong></h4><p>OAuth is a generalization of earlier protocols like Kerberos and WS-Trust for Web service security. The Token Service is known as the OAuth Authorization Server, the KDC, and the Security Token Service (STS), respectively, in those and OAuth. Clients are actively involved in obtaining tokens in each of these protocols. However, there are times when customers are passive rather than active. WS-Federation, which built an identity on top of WS-Trust to provide identity to passive clients like Web browsers, is an example of this. OpenID Connect is currently used for this as well. As a consequence of this, the OpenID Connect Provider—an OAuth Authorization Server that is capable of supporting OpenID Connect—is an STS that is capable of supporting passive clients. A Federation Service is another name for an STS that provides support for passive clients. Consequently, the Token Service in OAuth and OpenID Connect fulfills the Neo-security Architecture\'s two roles.</p><p>The OpenID Connect protocol is housed in the Token Service of the Curity Identity Server because internal single sign-on (SSO) access to cloud services like Office 365 and others requires a separate Federation Service these days.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/U65aoHjbxVSWDGTpzFE6SBHb_whp8AK7ueKsOlGWbqmX9j3pLxfW6MhnGPfaV9bsg7ySwArThQMU9CSaFumnFNIpJAIHDJUflGquQab3lXLXrPFivNBLuY9XX3RK03j0CxS3L7AuWACA2ex38nhLL00\" alt=\"identity-management-system\"></figure><h4><strong>The User Management Service</strong></h4><p>User identity data is needed by many systems. Even though a Federation Service and STS can sometimes be used to send this data to those systems, the data is frequently required at points where those systems are not involved. When a user uses federated authentication, a Federation Service and STS are only involved in a transaction. Systems may need user information after or before authentication. The STS and Federation Service\'s endpoints cannot be used to obtain this kind of information in these situations. A User Management Service is needed to accomplish this in the Identity System.</p><p>An abstraction of one or more Identity Repositories is a User Management Service. It lets you manage users by allowing you to \"Create, Retrieve, Update, and Delete\" (CRUD) user data. To add user information to tokens, a Federation Service or STS can use a User Management Service; However, outside of the Identity System, its primary customers are In order to provide additional information about a user that is required to make a fine-grained authorization decision, a client, for instance, might serve as the Policy Decision Point (described below). A cloud service that requires information about a user who has not yet accessed it in order for an administrator to locate and grant permissions or a license to that user is another example.</p><p>The standards-based CRUD interface that the User Management Service exposes is necessary for this abstraction to be interoperable. A System for Cross-domain Identity Management (SCIM) or Simple Cloud Identity Management, as SCIM was originally known, is the best option out of the few that are available. A resource-oriented API is made available by this lightweight RESTful protocol for carrying out CRUD operations on groups and users. Additionally, the API allows for precision updates to specific attributes as well as bulk updates (a process known as patching). For widespread interoperability, SCIM also defines a normative set of user and group attributes. Despite the fact that this protocol is older than the others discussed in this paper, it is supported by more than a dozen open-source and commercially available products; Additionally, these have been subjected to numerous public interop tests; and the protocol has been submitted to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for approval as an Internet standard.</p><p>Service Provisioning Markup Language (SPML) is one of the available provisioning protocols in addition to SCIM. However, SPML, in particular, is not supported by any major cloud service provider and has not received much industry adoption. There are LDAP-specific bindings for SOAP, JSON, and other protocols that do not offer the advantages of interoperability or widespread reuse. A User Management Service ought to implement at least SCIM for these reasons and the opposite for SCIM.</p><h2><strong>Conclusion</strong></h2><p>Identity management is a complicated process. It is easier to map requirements onto functions when the various aspects of identity are broken down into separate logical components. The IMS covers all of the use cases that come up when building large-scale mobile, web, and API-driven applications architecturally.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1676553480.jpg', 'identity-management-system', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'identity-management-system', NULL, NULL, 'Ankur', NULL, '1', NULL, '2023-02-16 18:48:00', '2023-02-16 18:48:00'),
(54, 'Identity Management System - Inbox Infotech', 'In today\'s digital world, identity management has become an essential part of every organization\'s security strategy. An identity management system (IMS) is a framework that enables organizations to manage the digital identities of employees, customers, and partners efficiently.', '<p>In today\'s digital world, identity management has become an essential part of every organization\'s security strategy. An&nbsp;<a href=\"https://inboxtechs.com/\">identity management system</a> (IMS) is a framework that enables organizations to manage the digital identities of employees, customers, and partners efficiently. An IMS allows organizations to control access to their resources, data, and applications by creating and managing unique identities and permissions.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/zZlIHkJhfSiMj-mE1D8A5M8OatfA-aa8UQn1BxqbhqCEYGOiP5hOdJd8qNz9fvAOOAPUaz8aNHA_5O3rqF-pCWv9JNqwtnm5f1CycqZ6mTB3AxuY99HsKDlzzHIxwXPGgQ23mJ3JdrOAHkjx8VqoLU8\" alt=\"identity-management-system\"></figure><h4><strong>An Identity Management System typically includes the following components:</strong></h4><ol><li><strong>Identity and Access Management (IAM): </strong>IAM is a subset of an identity management system that deals with managing digital identities, authentication, and access control. It involves creating and managing user accounts, assigning roles and permissions, and enforcing access policies.</li><li><strong>Single Sign-On (SSO):&nbsp;</strong>SSO is a feature of an identity management system that enables users to access multiple applications with a single set of login credentials. SSO reduces the need for users to remember multiple passwords and improves user experience.</li></ol><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/F4xZ25_55kD3kxlgIqJadCPf6QLDWBjeIbkUS3EKf2RNwVXSWc1ZXOh55r5Hi6x6KGJNLh486za9TYHb2ml0Lbx3693P0MMepgMJF3OksB3eGxdtzZoTxafZXhpkfKRCNLRqURcGBdMvbFYgA6k7Cr0\" alt=\"identity-management-system\"></figure><ol><li><strong>Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA):</strong>&nbsp;MFA is an additional layer of security that requires users to provide two or more authentication factors to access resources. MFA can include something the user knows (such as a password), something the user has (such as a security token), or something the user is (such as a biometric scan).</li><li><strong>Identity Governance and Administration (IGA): </strong>IGA is a process that ensures that user access rights are appropriate for their role and responsibilities within the organization. It involves defining access policies, monitoring access, and auditing access rights.</li><li><strong>Privileged Access Management (PAM): </strong>PAM is a set of policies and technologies for managing privileged access to critical systems and data. It involves creating and managing privileged accounts, monitoring privileged access, and enforcing access policies.</li></ol><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/ODRT6T7I5olc7qeKuHLwOILF9M15UQfRy0a1FZUE_uMELo7QbR7LBgPMoVD-zuEb87keAGT6EydRd154z63Eqk4S1BAPs9iQTctdtU3x25_LZoSCgh-MPxwCoxAxCSZ60TsVay3y-wn-PD67i6hoOhQ\" alt=\"identity-management-system\"></figure><h4><strong>Implementing an identity management system has several benefits, including:</strong></h4><ol><li><strong>Improved security:</strong> The identity management system provides a framework for enforcing strong access control policies, which reduces the risk of data breaches and unauthorized access.</li><li><strong>Compliance:</strong> The identity management system helps organizations comply with regulations such as GDPR, HIPAA, and SOX, which require organizations to protect user data and control access to sensitive information.</li><li><strong>Improved user experience:</strong> SSO and MFA improve user experience by reducing the need for users to remember multiple passwords and improving the security of user accounts.</li><li><strong>Increased productivity:</strong> The identity management system enables organizations to manage user access more efficiently, reducing the time spent on administrative tasks and allowing employees to focus on their core responsibilities.</li><li><strong>Cost savings:</strong> The identity management system reduces the cost of managing user accounts, reducing the need for manual administration and support.</li></ol><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/oXVOJ1NYYxuC2FnOc432idBjmaqaexSquiIYYY87LyLLqlBuzTzvxQCFcUY-l46UNdg4ruQVUuwjCaAJ71Z_kz8ZNxuFbRvwkS1Lk49PADdGJ_2npFgcsg1P5FWYG0gCDtsiualsRce_FL3cPtVmo5c\" alt=\"identity-management-system\"></figure><p>In conclusion, an identity management system is a crucial component of any organization\'s security strategy. It enables organizations to manage digital identities, control access to resources, and enforce access policies. The identity management system provides several benefits, including improved security, compliance, user experience, productivity, and cost savings. Organizations should consider implementing an&nbsp;<a href=\"https://goo.gl/maps/EK1AefjPKRLLoHcR7\">identity management system</a> to ensure the security of their digital assets and protect user data.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1676612895.jpg', 'identity-management-system', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'identity-management-system-india', NULL, NULL, 'Ankur', 'Ankur', '1', NULL, '2023-02-17 11:18:15', '2023-02-17 11:24:52'),
(55, 'What Is Purchase Order Management? - Inbox Infotech', 'Good inventory management practices must be enforced if profitability, productivity, and efficiency are to be maintained. Businesses with purchasing inefficiencies have a harder time serving their customers, whether it\'s managing physical goods and supply chains or internal indirect procurement processes.', '<p>Good inventory management practices must be enforced if profitability, productivity, and efficiency are to be maintained. Businesses with purchasing inefficiencies have a harder time serving their customers, whether it\'s managing physical goods and supply chains or internal indirect procurement processes.</p><p>Stock management necessitates the utilization of efficient purchase order procedures in direct procurement. One is required for internal purchasing and approval procedures with indirect procurement; The entire system may fall apart if there isn\'t a set of measures to make each step of the purchase order process easier. The company will as a result lose its competitive advantage, misallocate resources, and mismanage money.</p><p>You can organize your purchase order activities in a number of different ways and with the help of a few helpful hints. The stages of managing purchase orders across the distribution network are outlined in this brief definition of <a href=\"https://inboxtechs.com/\">purchase order management</a>.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/WBq2PxWptbR0FnblNA1SnxZPuGp9dQHLpdR-0g1v2ONg36-_yl4vp3UIzevTAXRc12o0TPMs45mou1nyVD_NhC6zvNIzCnmQuBHwRu_R0OeMsS_-ldvt-nFG_O8vPp1_maxlCYtBsSrbxQ9s1pJh2t4\" alt=\"purchase-order-management\"></figure><p><strong>The Purchase Order Management Process</strong></p><p>Your purchase order procedure is essential to your success, no matter how big or small your business is. Procurement delays can cost your business a lot more money than you might think because vendors may leave if you don\'t approve requests on time.</p><p>Optimizing your purchase order process is one of the easiest and most effective ways to grow your business. Let\'s get into the fundamentals.</p><h4><strong>What Is Procurement?</strong></h4><p>Business strategy includes procurement, which is the process of acquiring goods or services from outside sources or vendors. Throughout this process, clients consider a variety of aspects, including timing, quantity, and quality.</p><p>Using the procurement process, which ensures that a product is purchased correctly, businesses can avoid scams and fraud.</p><p><strong>The Two Types Of Activities That Fall Under Procurement Are:</strong></p><h4><strong>Direct Procurement</strong></h4><p>This is buying things like raw materials that go into making a finished product. Supply chain management may be affected.</p><h4><strong>Indirect Procurement</strong></h4><p>This is a purchase that has nothing to do with production and includes things like standard office supplies, software solutions, and maintenance for heavy equipment.</p><h4><strong>What Is a Purchase Order?</strong></h4><p>Businesses can better understand and keep track of the products and services they have requested with the help of purchase orders. It is a legal agreement between the seller and the buyer.</p><p>Managers can track important details like quantity, delivery instructions, pricing, terms, and delivery dates with purchase orders. When the existing stock is about to run out, additional supplies are required, or a particular item is required, a purchase order is issued.</p><p>From the moment a requirement is identified to the point of sale or delivery, the entire process of creating, approving, validating, managing, and tracking purchase orders is referred to as the \"purchase order process.\"</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/EVx_n2HkXlUnWj6q5H_cXeaUiVYdgvfSyuhbgl561seys_WC4Nw9hH3YnC36rTpP9Uy0l7ZHEgUa5_pZxXSjCGNZkhSENnWr7xNIyq1YDWyQgT4qpxDv9GU7ltUXgSxj13jGyQkLtckVjIcFuYoC5Lg\" alt=\"purchase-order-management\"></figure><h4><strong>What Is the Purchase Order Process?</strong></h4><p>A typical purchase order cycle consists of the following steps:</p><p>recognizing a need</p><p>submitting a request for purchase or purchase request (RFP)</p><p>Selection of vendors</p><p>Choosing a term and issuing a purchase order</p><p>Making purchase orders</p><p>shipment receipt and quality control</p><p>completing the purchase order and comparing the items received to the order</p><h4><strong>What is Purchase Order Management?</strong></h4><p>A set of established standards and procedures for purchase order management ensure that accurate and up-to-date information about single or multiple purchase orders is always accessible.</p><p>For achieving procurement goals within budgetary constraints, these standards and procedures are essential. Utilizing specialized tools and communication channels, they include establishing specific actions and privileges for all participants in the supply chain and acting on them.</p><p>To ensure that employees adhere to standard operating procedures before completing procurement orders, a lot of businesses have established policies for managing purchase orders.</p><p>Standard methods for managing purchase orders include email and spreadsheets, which are frequently preceded by phone calls; However, in this scenario, unneeded issues arise as a result of minor information changes.</p><p>For a small project, repeated communication over the same purchase order may be sufficient; however, as the project grows, it becomes unsustainable.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/YxQ30rBzu_QD1XpRgCWbupGQ5YakyOQNsmdrHebkoIieWIjwncIDvasa8llh0n4e7AHE3x5T09zPFdAWAhT669YZQ0x8J2P-eZ_Xe5Kdf85YKHzT8jimCxl3UOslikFdPVLqLoddNRMJARSfIEUWpOA\" alt=\"purchase-order-management\"></figure><h4><strong>Why Is Purchase Order Management Important?</strong></h4><p>Because it enables a business to track and manage inventory levels as well as the purchasing process, a purchase order management system is essential. Such frameworks guarantee that merchandise is requested as soon as possible and is accessible when required, while likewise ensuring that the organization doesn\'t over-buy or request past the point of no return.</p><p>By streamlining the ordering process and making it simpler for suppliers to comprehend what is required and when purchase order management can also contribute to improved relationships with suppliers. By reducing the amount of inventory held at any given time, a good purchase order management system will also help improve cash flow.</p><h4><strong>How Does Purchase Order Management Work?</strong></h4><p>The process of managing purchase orders can be broken down into five steps for a business. Planning and designing the purchase order is the first step. This step usually takes place in the department of purchasing, where buyers make a request for goods or services.</p><p>The requisition is then forwarded to the subsequent department, typically engineering or production. They will confirm that they require the items on the requisition and are able to make them. A purchase order must be created and approved by the accounting department as the next step.</p><p>After that, the purchasing department sends the necessary approvals to the supplier and verifies that they have been obtained. After that, the supplier will ship the goods to the business, and the accounting department will send the invoice to the right account when it gets there.</p><h4><strong>How Your Company Can Benefit from Purchase Order Management</strong></h4><p>Management of purchase orders is a crucial part of running a successful business, especially for expanding businesses. Because every company has limited resources at any given time, it is essential to maximize their use, monitor expenditures, and streamline procedures.</p><p>Still, a problem is the lack of standardization and organization in the creation and submission of purchase orders. Due to a combination of paper documents and databases, e-mails, and even phone conversations, stakeholders no longer have access to current purchase information.</p><p>Because it assists in the prevention of errors and fraud as well as the reduction of excessive administrative levels, purchase order management offers a solution to these issues. Making well-informed purchases and gaining a better understanding of spending are essential aspects of managing purchase orders.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/qt7F4e5dsgDQdd12v2PqyNX-7iCNU96X58nA4D0ktBere-EHb6stC9o_5mt8BCEQ8_Yc0tkNSR6a7eI3W7Skr4m58vDRb1DJgjlFdj2O_0o7lDZ_ow5jvEu2kliGyf_8LLE0mR32Bjf6jAPn6dDwFeI\" alt=\"purchase-order-management\"></figure><h4><strong>Put it into Practice</strong></h4><p>A company\'s official purchase order to an outside supplier is a legally binding document that contains all of the information required to purchase goods or services.</p><p>In order to guarantee that each purchase is pertinent, timely, and cost-effective, businesses implement and personalize purchase order management procedures. It is essential to make certain that employees follow a set of standard operating procedures and make use of the most cutting-edge technological options.</p><p>Automation allows for faster processing of purchase orders. It ensures that every payment is justified, reduces errors, speeds up the process, and provides managers and others involved in the procurement process with a real-time status update.</p><p>Optimizing <a href=\"https://goo.gl/maps/EK1AefjPKRLLoHcR7\">purchase order management</a> requires careful inspection, guidelines, the creation of a central vendor database, a suitable approval procedure, the use of budget-based expense limits, and making status updates available to employees.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1677073601.png', 'purchase-order-management', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'purchase-order-management', NULL, NULL, 'Ankur', 'Ankur', '1', NULL, '2023-02-22 19:16:41', '2023-02-22 19:19:43'),
(56, 'What is Fleet Management System? - Inbox Infotech', 'A fleet management system (FMS) is a software solution designed to help businesses manage their vehicle fleets efficiently and effectively. It is a comprehensive system that provides real-time tracking, monitoring, and management of vehicles, drivers, and other assets such as fuel and maintenance.', '<h4><strong>Key Takeaways</strong></h4><p>From vehicle acquisition to asset disposal, fleet management is a set of procedures that give businesses access to and control over all information pertaining to their vehicles and other assets. As technology has improved, more businesses have turned to fleet management software to manage the cost of ownership, improve maintenance planning, and provide better visibility into asset and vehicle utilization. As the role of the fleet manager changes, more businesses are finding that digital processes that streamline activities and eliminate inefficient manual tasks are beneficial.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/J0pAnRGdEM5DvSuv1zV3Z-Y7Qd8IgEFeXPjv-_IGf8HjBVzpfPGaf2Y4ga6GBtuU72Vunj5MZOfSfQ7GblVHsK0dbO5SA8GPT1P17EC7V6INX0VMF3ikyYnsMHnImEyM8lIGittF08qF-3w5Ed0_FS0\" alt=\"fleet-management-system\"></figure><h4><strong>What Is Fleet Management System?</strong></h4><p>Over the past ten years, fleet management has undergone a complete transformation as businesses have begun to realize the benefits of an efficient fleet to their operations. Fleet management teams are now in charge of a wide range of activities, including driver management, compliance management, operational efficiency, and environmental impact, in addition to procuring and maintaining vehicles.</p><p>More and more teams are turning to fleet management system because it gives them a place to record and access the information they need to keep up with the ever-changing demands of their job as the role of the fleet manager continues to evolve.</p><p>The right software can give fleet managers complete visibility into all of their fleet operations, help them streamline day-to-day tasks, and help them find deeper issues that affect the performance of the fleet and the business.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/AqR3KDiRMGedcPejl4BEbKrDDNUxl2lT8YYvsbTV2uUfbSGMO5iNuU6zdrKlsFQqj_BVqZ-6mHQRLKxmFkqREMQn5IA8n4hRjiNK1O0HP9VgNGx791EqBE32_I3c9_l_dmUUoceyXzkg_TbO7Q39YLo\" alt=\"fleet-management-system\"></figure><h4><strong>What Is A Fleet Manager Responsible For?</strong></h4><p>Fleet managers are responsible for performing routine vehicle service and maintenance, among other things, to ensure that everything runs as smoothly as possible at all times. Making inspections, scheduling maintenance, reporting, and other tasks are all examples of this.</p><p>In addition, fleet managers are responsible for establishing organizational guidelines for the purchase and retirement of vehicles, setting goals (and expectations) for driver performance, and paying attention to key metrics that provide valuable insight into the performance of the fleet as well as individual vehicles and drivers.</p><p>The role of the fleet manager may also encompass asset utilization and route planning, as well as fuel consumption and costs. The company\'s telematics system or fleet management system is typically owned by the fleet manager.</p><h4><strong>Digitization &amp; Fleet Management Software</strong></h4><p>Due to the ongoing development of fleet management software, mobile applications, and a deeper level of system integration,&nbsp;the <a href=\"https://inboxtechs.com/\">fleet management system</a> has become increasingly digitalized over the past ten years. The following are some key areas where our fleet management solutions can digitize your entire operation:</p><p><strong>Maintenance Planning:</strong> A digitized schedule enables fleet managers to identify excessive wear and tear before it becomes a major problem and ensures that vehicles receive routine maintenance. This, thus, diminishes vehicle free time and upkeep costs.</p><p><strong>DVIR:</strong> Drivers can quickly and effectively report vehicle and maintenance issues with Digital Vehicle Inspection Reports (DVIR). By eliminating unanticipated downtime and drawing attention to problem areas in real-time, photo upload capabilities aid in keeping vehicles on the road.</p><p><strong>Dispatch/Job Management:</strong> You can automate customer communication and create daily run sheets, assign one-time jobs to your team, monitor progress, and manage digital job management from a single application. In addition, these tools help to streamline the workflow of the process and include proof of delivery (a photo and signature).</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/9AXxsBgxS9LmL4uD-fqGQumgZR34j3CG27bycIGtvwvd2gjByOYp__9QztcojsCCvQ1ow3-WSunQXeQdcAXZzjsJa9GfhF8NP3GWGnCV0a4BtgWhkjnSIRsC2w8pJVsNksA3CuR-CgXV_Ab58KoEUWM\" alt=\"fleet-management-system\"></figure><p><strong>HOS/ELD:&nbsp;</strong>Electronic logging devices (ELD) for hours-of-service (HOS) are required by law for many fleets that must keep a driver record of duty status. The management of driver hours is made simpler and job assignments are made easier with an ELD solution that is integrated with your fleet management system.</p><p>Safety for Drivers Real-time data on driver behavior and the automatic creation of driver risk profiles aid fleet managers in identifying high-risk drivers and developing individualized coaching programs. Driver safety league tables that can be used in safe driving incentive programs are another feature of many fleet management systems.</p><p>Because they function as a single source for gaining real-time visibility into the state of the entire fleet, these kinds of solutions make the job of a fleet manager much easier to manage. Additionally, when your fleet management software is integrated with other applications utilized by the business, it makes it simpler to transfer information throughout the organization. This facilitates better and more informed decision-making, increases efficiency, and speeds up the transfer of data.</p><h4><strong>Why Do Businesses Use Fleet Management Software?</strong></h4><p>Benefits of fleet management software include improved driver behavior, cost analysis, and real-time visibility into the location and performance of the fleet. The data presented by modern fleet management software is easily understood by businesses and goes beyond location tracking to provide insight into vehicle performance and efficiency.</p><p>Software for fleet management can assist you in obtaining objective information about driver safety, highlighting risky behaviors like speeding or harsh braking, and determining which drivers require additional training. Your fleet\'s compliance with federal and state laws must also be maintained.</p><p>Fleet managers can get the most out of their assets by implementing preventative maintenance schedules thanks to the technology\'s ability to support proactive maintenance efforts. Numerous organizations additionally use versatile applications that empower moment information move and openness, thus assisting them with rapidly distinguishing issues that might have gone unseen or transformed into bigger issues.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/3NXB2_nY93tbsPA1cUIqttxoKrTJCHDJU6IjcaZVUR5R3RXTQ_MFeLcJlg5B71pCu6JG6DqDyLZd2aN6fIp2pbQzLfgMq0nAlTU8OEg7v6qSkwkgPjUe8KtxTKPnBVlW7BWc8cZwJMu3RJE-KixNUrg\"></figure><h4><strong>What Should Fleet Managers Look For In Fleet Management Software?</strong></h4><p>A cloud-based&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fleet_Management_System\">fleet management system</a> should always be purchased by fleet managers. Putting away information in the cloud implies that data is open day in and day out/365 from any gadget and in any area with a functioning Web association. This is especially helpful for fleet managers who still need to keep an eye on the fleet despite spending a lot of time out in the field.</p><p>When switching fleet management software or purchasing for the first time, a company should look for the following fundamental features:</p><p><strong>Automation tools:</strong> Drivers and fleet managers can be alerted in real-time of route changes, vehicles that are off course, and unsafe driving behaviors through custom alerts and in-cab notifications.</p><p><strong>Data Insights:&nbsp;</strong>A data set is one thing. However, it is essential to be able to comprehend data and use it to make decisions. Using artificial intelligence, programmable dashboards, and reports can anticipate and highlight potential issues in advance.</p><p><strong>Safety Analytics:&nbsp;</strong>Safety is an important part of any software platform for fleet management. It is essential to maintain a safe workplace to know where your vehicles are and how they are operated.</p><p><strong>Performance Measurement:&nbsp;</strong>If you want to keep costs for your fleet under control, one of the most crucial aspects is probably how well your vehicles perform and are used. Fleet management software helps you get the most out of your investment in a variety of ways, including performing routine maintenance and identifying performance issues with your vehicle before they become a problem.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1677146804.png', 'fleet-management-system', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'fleet-management-system', NULL, NULL, 'Ankur', NULL, '1', NULL, '2023-02-23 15:36:44', '2023-02-23 15:36:44'),
(57, 'Freight Management System: A Comprehensive Overview', 'Freight management is an essential part of logistics and supply chain management. It refers to the process of organizing, planning, and controlling the movement of goods from one place to another. In recent years, with the increasing demand for faster, safer, and more efficient transportation of goods, the need for an effective freight management system has become more important than ever.', '<p>Freight management is an essential part of logistics and supply chain management. It refers to the process of organizing, planning, and controlling the movement of goods from one place to another. In recent years, with the increasing demand for faster, safer, and more efficient transportation of goods, the need for an effective&nbsp;<a href=\"https://inboxtechs.com/\">freight management system</a> has become more important than ever. In this article, we will explore what a freight management system is, its benefits, its key features, and more.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/xVhH_4zb-OjOCc1LDuUViyanbfVSf7rsnYhXRKcCuVlnMIIjpf53xro2KsjsD2-aU_RrWubbFYL1eYBAwIFe2nY60mqJbiR_OIYobDuHySTuK3DPi1dCIr9yMIPyWJoJ_4L47tqPGAQK69o6MNJ6Y2Q\" alt=\"freight-management-system\"></figure><h4><strong>What is a Freight Management System?</strong></h4><p>A freight management system (FMS) is a software application that automates and streamlines the process of managing freight transportation operations. It provides a centralized platform that allows shippers, carriers, and other stakeholders to collaborate, communicate, and manage freight movements in real time. Freight management system typically includes a range of features such as shipment tracking, route optimization, load planning, carrier selection, and invoice management.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/bNbqgAoiGTuh9LCYXSL-eUfOi9-2gNY5Dpt06VAEzletu0ajmcFKAywJBGLn94U7eoq0q0wBHtRYnO53KzX8IG7KJC7CX0m4j5jdawh63j-XNTqQGPoxQ5p8IXcxSv3CbJ60DbcOk_5NIWhdHn4y0yw\" alt=\"freight-management-system\"></figure><h4><strong>Benefits of a Freight Management System</strong></h4><p>A freight management system can bring numerous benefits to businesses that rely on transportation and logistics operations. Some of the key benefits are as follows:</p><ol><li><strong>Improved Efficiency:</strong> Freight management systems can automate manual processes, reduce paperwork, and streamline transportation operations. This can help businesses to reduce the time and effort required to manage freight movements, which can lead to improved efficiency and productivity.&nbsp;</li><li><strong>Cost Savings:&nbsp;</strong>A freight management system can help businesses to reduce transportation costs by optimizing routes, consolidating shipments, and selecting the most cost-effective carriers. This can lead to significant cost savings and improved profitability.</li><li><strong>Enhanced Visibility: </strong>An FMS can provide real-time visibility into the status of shipments, allowing businesses to track shipments, monitor delivery times, and proactively address any issues that may arise.</li><li><strong>Better Collaboration:&nbsp;</strong>A freight management system can facilitate communication and collaboration between shippers, carriers, and other stakeholders. This can help to improve relationships and ensure that everyone is working towards the same goal.</li><li><strong>Improved Customer Service:&nbsp;</strong>A freight management system can help businesses to provide better customer service by improving delivery times, reducing errors, and providing accurate and timely information about shipments.</li></ol><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/tKsDrVdlHsyMxC9eIMKZS0GSLkFEktm-K7uK8QLgA_2fkV2bx_5qn33wEjWwofdtp865SFO1hmKjiJZzz4POnEZ1joRYBX1Cigfv84_s0DtGehgdZMpl6w36XxGoutC24Tk02uU2pzjNStEyWNzb-Ss\" alt=\"freight-management-system\"></figure><h4><strong>Key Features of a Freight Management System</strong></h4><p>A freight management system typically includes a range of features that are designed to streamline and automate transportation operations. Some of the key features are as follows:</p><ol><li><strong>Shipment Management: </strong>A freight management system should allow businesses to create and manage shipments, track shipments in real time, and generate reports on shipment status.</li><li><strong>Carrier Management: </strong>An FMS should provide a centralized platform for managing carriers, including carrier selection, rate negotiations, and carrier performance tracking.</li><li><strong>Route Optimization: </strong>The freight management system should be able to optimize routes based on factors such as distance, traffic, and delivery times to reduce transportation costs and improve delivery times.</li><li><strong>Load Planning: </strong>An FMS should allow businesses to optimize load planning to ensure that shipments are loaded efficiently and safely.</li><li><strong>Invoice Management:</strong> The freight management system should provide automated invoice management capabilities, including invoice generation, payment processing, and dispute resolution.</li></ol><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/aqPHRMTziv5910hBNQqSyFa0WOiCg7W_RWxDHfRW32M4JCh49HuQkTNjpMG_g9ULPK4NZeBbZkNw4l7lfu060rjLMuw_IziqCmWA7s6ltapsu0_cS7xiRpDexM02PVeSLSx1VS9MZDg7etMl2oEfRcg\" alt=\"freight-management-system\"></figure><h4><strong>Industries That Use Freight Management Systems</strong></h4><p>Freight management systems (FMS) are widely used across various industries that rely on efficient transportation and logistics operations. Here are some of the industries that use FMS:</p><ol><li><strong>Retail:</strong> The retail industry heavily relies on freight management systems to transport goods from manufacturers to distribution centers and retail stores. The freight management system can help retailers to optimize routes, reduce transportation costs, and improve delivery times.</li><li><strong>Manufacturing:</strong> Manufacturing companies use FMS to transport raw materials, finished products, and equipment between factories, warehouses, and suppliers. The freight management system can assist manufacturers to optimize inventory levels, reduce lead times, and improve supply chain visibility.</li><li><strong>E-commerce:</strong> E-commerce companies rely on FMS to manage the transportation of goods from warehouses to customers. FMS can help e-commerce businesses to optimize last-mile delivery, track shipments in real time, and provide accurate delivery estimates to customers.</li><li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> The healthcare industry uses a freight management system to transport medical supplies, equipment, and drugs between hospitals, clinics, and suppliers. FMS can help healthcare providers to manage inventory levels, reduce waste, and ensure the timely delivery of critical supplies.</li><li><strong>Food and Beverage:&nbsp;</strong>The food and beverage industry uses FMS to transport perishable goods between farms, processing plants, and retailers. FMS can help food and beverage companies to optimize temperature control, reduce spoilage, and ensure compliance with food safety regulations.</li><li><strong>Construction:&nbsp;</strong>The construction industry uses FMS to transport building materials, equipment, and machinery to job sites. FMS can help construction companies to optimize load planning, reduce transportation costs, and improve the job site efficiency.</li><li><strong>Energy and Utilities:</strong> The energy and utilities industry uses FMS to transport equipment, materials, and supplies between sites. FMS can help energy and utility companies to optimize supply chain operations, reduce transportation costs, and improve delivery times.</li></ol><p>Overall, any industry that relies on transportation and logistics operations can benefit from using a freight management system.</p><p><strong>Conclusion</strong></p><p>In conclusion, a freight management system is an essential tool for businesses that rely on transportation and logistics operations. An FMS can help businesses to improve efficiency, reduce costs, enhance visibility, and provide better customer service. By automating and streamlining transportation operations, businesses can focus on their core activities and achieve their strategic goals. If you are looking to improve your transportation and logistics operations, a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://goo.gl/maps/EK1AefjPKRLLoHcR7\">freight management system</a> may be the solution you need.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1677223520.png', 'freight-management-system', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'freight-management-system', NULL, NULL, 'Ankur', 'Ankur', '1', NULL, '2023-02-24 12:52:22', '2023-02-24 12:58:03');
